snippet.textDisplay:
I don't know when Hyundai started selling cars in the US, but I can remember when they were first imported to Australia in 1988. They were butt-ugly, but with a Mitsubishi engine and a robust interior, they managed to survive the original scepticism. Then the Excel came out for around 13K (AUD) with power steering & aircon. All of a sudden they sold like hot-cakes and seemed to be everywhere on the road.


Fast forward to 2020 and a Hyundai is a car that can hold it's own against any Japanese brand. I never thought that they would make it this far.
snippet.textOriginal:
I don't know when Hyundai started selling cars in the US, but I can remember when they were first imported to Australia in 1988. They were butt-ugly, but with a Mitsubishi engine and a robust interior, they managed to survive the original scepticism. Then the Excel came out for around 13K (AUD) with power steering & aircon. All of a sudden they sold like hot-cakes and seemed to be everywhere on the road.


Fast forward to 2020 and a Hyundai is a car that can hold it's own against any Japanese brand. I never thought that they would make it this far.
